{
  "texts": [
    "(13) (The corresponding optimization problem is not a QP, but is readily handled by convex optimization solvers developed in the 1990s [LVBL98b, NN94, Stu99, TTT99].)",
    "This formulation seems more natural, since a portfolio manager will often have a target risk in her mind, e.g., 8% annualized.",
    "This is the basic formulation that we recommend.",
    "There are many other ways to combine expected return and risk.",
    "For example, we can maximize the return/risk ratio, called the Sharpe ratio (with no benchmark) or information ratio (with a benchmark)."
  ]
}